'''Juan Camilo Hernández Suárez''' (born 20 April 1999), known simply as '''Cucho Hernández''', is a Colombian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]] or [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[La Liga]] club [[Real Betis]] and the [[Colombia national football team|Colombia national team]].

== Club career ==

===Early career===
Born in Pereira, Hernández played youth football for Indubolsas and was part of the [[Risaralda Department|Risaralda]] team that won the Pereira City Cup in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-02 |title=CUADROS DE HONOR TODOS |url=https://www.eldiario.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1.-CUADROS-DE-HONOR-TODOS-1-convertido.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702071801/https://www.eldiario.com.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/1.-CUADROS-DE-HONOR-TODOS-1-convertido.pdf |archive-date=2023-07-02 |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=eldiario.com}}</ref> He joined [[Deportivo Pereira]] in 2015 at the age of 15, catching the attention of the club after delivering impressive performances at the Pereira City Cup.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Guillermo Montenegro |first=Luis |date=2016-10-23 |title=ELESPECTADOR.COM |url=https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/otros-equipos/juan-camilo-hernandez-el-nino-que-manda-en-el-pereira-article-661845/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702054106/https://www.elespectador.com/deportes/futbol-colombiano/otros-equipos/juan-camilo-hernandez-el-nino-que-manda-en-el-pereira-article-661845/ |archive-date=2023-07-02 |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=ELESPECTADOR.COM |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolred.com/torneo-aguila/juan-camilo-hernandez-el-nino-que-es-goleador-del-pereira-en-la-b+16545770|title=Juan Camilo Hernández, el 'niño' que es goleador del Pereira en la B|trans-title=Juan Camilo Hernández, the 'kid' who is the goalscorer of Pereira in the ''B''|publisher=Futbol Red|language=es|date=26 March 2016|access-date=9 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118073102/http://www.futbolred.com/torneo-aguila/juan-camilo-hernandez-el-nino-que-es-goleador-del-pereira-en-la-b+16545770|archive-date=18 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his first team debut on 6 April 2015 at 15 years old, starting in a 2–1 home win against [[Deportes Quindío]] for the [[Categoría Primera B]] championship.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Molina |first=Felipe |date=2019-05-23 |title=Así descubrieron al 'Cucho', el '10' de Colombia en el Mundial |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/05/22/futbol/1558555976_644705.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530061911/https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/05/22/futbol/1558555976_644705.html |archive-date=2019-05-30 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref>

Hernández scored his first senior goal on 5 September 2015, netting his team's first in a 3–2 away win against [[Real Santander]]. After finishing [[2015 Categoría Primera B season|his first season]] with three goals, he was named captain of the team the [[2016 Categoría Primera B season|following year]] at just 17 years old. He would end up scoring 20 times during the regular season, being the tournament's top goalscorer; despite playing more as an [[Attacking Midfielder|attacking midfielder]] than a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|centre-forward]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=10. Juan Camilo Hernandez, Granada |url=https://www.foxsports.com/stories/soccer/10-juan-camilo-hernandez-granada |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=FOX Sports |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Molina |first=Felipe |date=2019-05-23 |title=Así descubrieron al 'Cucho', el '10' de Colombia en el Mundial |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2019/05/22/futbol/1558555976_644705.html |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Hornets keeping close eye on starlet Hernandez |url=https://www.watfordobserver.co.uk/sport/15666557.watford-keep-close-eye-on-huesca-loanee-star-juan-camilo-hernandez-after-impressive-start-in-spain/ |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=Watford Observer |language=en}}</ref> Highlights included a [[hat-trick]] in a 3–0 home victory over [[Tigres F.C.]] on 3 July 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-07-21 |title=Columbus Crew acquires 23-year-old forward Juan Camilo "Cucho" Hernandez in record transaction |url=https://www.columbuscrew.com/news/columbus-crew-acquires-23-year-old-forward-juan-camilo-cucho-hernandez-in-record |access-date=2023-09-03 |website=[[Columbus Crew]]}}</ref>

===Granada and loan to América de Cali===
On 22 December 2016 Hernández joined [[América de Cali]] on loan from [[Granada CF]], after signing for the latter side in September. for a reported £200k.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena2.com.co/futbol/noticias/juan-camilo-hern%C3%A1ndez-lleg%C3%B3-al-am%C3%A9rica-de-cal-104351|title=Juan Camilo Hernández llegó al América de Cali|trans-title=Juan Camilo Hernández arrived at América de Cali|publisher=Antena 2|language=es|date=22 December 2016|access-date=9 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Leventhal |first=Adam |date=2022-03-17 |title=Cucho Hernandez’s journey to Watford’s first team: Debut at 15, early comparisons to Aguero and his nickname origins |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3184982/2022/03/17/cucho-hernandezs-journey-to-watfords-first-team-debut-at-15-early-comparisons-to-aguero-and-his-nickname-origins/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=2025-05-05 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He made his [[Categoría Primera A]] debut on 23 February 2017, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in a 2–0 home loss against [[Jaguares de Córdoba]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.futbolred.com/liga-aguila/america-perdio-0-2-con-jaguares-en-la-liga-i-2017+16827461|title=América y un partido para el olvido: Jaguares lo superó 0–2|trans-title=América and a match to forget: Jaguares overcame them by 0–2|publisher=Futbol Red|language=es|date=23 February 2017|access-date=9 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320015317/http://www.futbolred.com/liga-aguila/america-perdio-0-2-con-jaguares-en-la-liga-i-2017+16827461|archive-date=20 March 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Hernández scored his first goal in the top flight of Colombian football on 3 June 2017, netting the game's only goal in an away win over [[Deportivo Pasto]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Grueso |first=Hector Fabio |date=2017-06-06 |title='Cucho' Hernández: "La gente no creía en mí, ni en el América" |url=https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2017/06/06/futbol/1496716532_892441.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702085546/https://colombia.as.com/colombia/2017/06/06/futbol/1496716532_892441.html |archive-date=2023-07-02 |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=Diario AS |language=es-co}}</ref>

===Watford===
After Granada was sold to [[Jiang Lizhang]], former owner [[Gino Pozzo]] assigned his federative rights to [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] ahead of the 2017–18 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.granadahoy.com/granadacf/Cucho-Hernandez-sono-Granada-Huesca_0_1152485229.html|title=Cucho Hernández, que sonó para el Granada, al Huesca|trans-title=Cucho Hernández, targeted by Granada, to Huesca|publisher=Granada Hoy|language=es|date=9 July 2017|access-date=18 July 2020}}</ref>

====Loans to Huesca, Mallorca and Getafe====
On 8 July 2017, Hernández moved to [[Segunda División]] side [[SD Huesca]] on loan for one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdhuesca.es/noticia/cucho-hernandez-se-incorpora-a-la-sd-huesca|title="Cucho" Hernández se incorpora a la SD Huesca|trans-title="Cucho" Hernández joins SD Huesca|publisher=SD Huesca|language=es|date=8 July 2017|access-date=9 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141215/https://www.sdhuesca.es/noticia/cucho-hernandez-se-incorpora-a-la-sd-huesca|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the [[2017–18 Segunda División|2017-2018 season]], he scored 16 goals and was named the league's player of the month in November,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2017-12-15 |title='Cucho' Hernández, Mejor Jugador de LaLiga 1l2l3 en noviembre |url=https://www.laliga.com/noticias/cucho-hernandez-mejor-jugador-de-laliga-1l2l3-en-noviembre |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702080451/https://www.laliga.com/noticias/cucho-hernandez-mejor-jugador-de-laliga-1l2l3-en-noviembre |archive-date=2023-07-02 |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=Página web oficial de LaLiga {{!}} LaLiga |language=es}}</ref> while his team achieved their first-ever promotion to [[La Liga]]. On 4 June 2018, his loan was extended for a further season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sdhuesca.es/noticia/cucho-amplia-su-contrato-con-la-sd-huesca|title=Cucho amplía su contrato con la SD Huesca|trans-title=Cucho extends his contract with SD Huesca|publisher=SD Huesca|language=es|date=4 June 2018|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622004922/https://www.sdhuesca.es/noticia/cucho-amplia-su-contrato-con-la-sd-huesca|archive-date=22 June 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> and he made his top tier debut on 19 August by starting in a 2–1 away win against [[SD Eibar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/abci-eibar-huesca-liga-santander-201808191743_directo.html|title=Gallar alumbra el brillante debut del Huesca en Primera|trans-title=Gallar lights up the brilliant debut of Huesca in ''Primera''|publisher=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=19 August 2018|access-date=12 November 2018}}</ref>

Hernández scored his first goal in the main category of Spanish football on 2 September 2018, netting the opener in an 8–2 loss at [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2018/09/02/5b8c2d57e2704e75b48b4600.html|title=Barcelona bash Huesca for eight|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=2 September 2018|access-date=18 July 2020}}</ref> He finished [[2018–19 La Liga|2018–19]] with four goals in 34 appearances, as his side was immediately relegated back.

On 26 August 2019, Hernández signed a new long term contract with Watford<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.watfordfc.com/news/official-new-contract-loan-move-for-cucho|title=Official: New Contract & Loan Move For Cucho|work=watfordfc.com|date=26 August 2019|access-date=4 July 2021}}</ref> and joined [[RCD Mallorca]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/premier-league/1163236/watfords-cucho-hernandez-joins-mallorca-on-loan|title=Watford's Cucho Hernandez joins Mallorca on loan|work=FOX Sports|date=26 August 2019|access-date=26 August 2019|archive-date=13 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913234101/https://www.foxsportsasia.com/football/premier-league/1163236/watfords-cucho-hernandez-joins-mallorca-on-loan/|url-status=dead}}</ref> Having arrived at Mallorca with a hamstring injury, Hernández made his debut with the club on 7 December 2019, coming on as a substitute versus [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=García |first=Elena |date=2019-11-18 |title=El Cucho Hernández por fin entrena con el Mallorca |url=https://www.diariodemallorca.es/deportes/2019/11/18/cucho-hernandez-entrena-mallorca-2826727.html |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=[[Diario de Mallorca]] |language=es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-25 |title=Barcelona vs. Mallorca - Football Match Line-Ups - December 7, 2019 - ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups/_/gameId/550460 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225102441/https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups/_/gameId/550460 |archive-date=2021-12-25 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 15 February 2020 in a 1[[2018–19 La Liga|–]]0 victory against [[Deportivo Alavés|Alavés]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-25 |title=Mallorca vs. Alavés - Football Match Line-Ups - February 15, 2020 - ESPN |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups/_/gameId/550374 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425053906/https://www.espn.com/soccer/lineups/_/gameId/550374 |archive-date=2023-04-25 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=ESPN.com |language=en}}</ref> At the end of the [[2019–20 La Liga|2019–20]] season, Mallorca were relegated to the [[Segunda División]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-25 |title=Cucho 2019-2020 Match Logs |url=https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2019-2020/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210521183135/https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2019-2020/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |archive-date=2021-05-21 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref>

On 14 August 2020, Hernández remained in Spain and its first division, after joining [[Getafe CF]] on a [[2020–21 La Liga|season]]-long loan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.getafecf.com/Noticia/tabid/137/Article/6990/Cucho-Hernandez-cedido.aspx|title=Cucho Hernández, cedido|trans-title=Cucho Hernández, on loan|publisher=Getafe CF|language=es|date=14 August 2020|access-date=19 August 2020}}</ref> On 28 December 2020, Hernández was handed a four-match suspension for post-match statements that he made about the refereeing during the 25 October match against [[Granada CF|Granada]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-12-28 |title=Expediente nº 45 – 2020/21 |url=https://rfef.es/sites/default/files/sanciones/resolucion_expediente_no_45_2020-21.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815083609/https://www.rfef.es/sites/default/files/sanciones/resolucion_expediente_no_45_2020-21.pdf |archive-date=2022-08-15 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=rfef.es}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2020-12-28 |title=Cuatro partidos al Cucho Hernández por criticar a los árbitros y ninguno a Koeman |url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/primera-division/2020/12/28/5fea2396268e3ee5168b4580.html |access-date=2023-12-14 |website=MARCA |language=es}}</ref> Hernandez would also miss two months of the season due to suffering a fifth metatarsal fracture during the match against Atletico Madrid on 13 March 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-03-14 |title=Cucho Hernández estará tres meses de baja |url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/getafe/20210314/492703917269/cucho-hernandez-getafe-lesion.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210318135019/https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/getafe/20210314/492703917269/cucho-hernandez-getafe-lesion.html |archive-date=2021-03-18 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=Mundo Deportivo |language=es}}</ref> He would return to play the final two matches of the [[2019–20 La Liga|2020–21 La Liga season]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-25 |title=Cucho 2020-2021 Match Logs |url=https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2020-2021/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201121181254/https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2020-2021/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |archive-date=2020-11-21 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref>

====Return to Watford====

On 14 August 2021, Hernández scored on his [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] debut in their league opener against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], where [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] won 3–2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58124896|title=Watford 3–2 Aston Villa|website=bbc.co.uk|first=Ellie|last=Thomason|date=14 August 2021|access-date=14 August 2021}}</ref> On 9 April 2022, he suffered a hamstring injury; sidelining him for six weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hodgson: "The Second Goal Was A Killer Blow" |url=https://www.watfordfc.com/news/hodgson-the-second-goal-was-a-killer-blow |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=www.watfordfc.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Fish |first=Hal |date=2022-04-15 |title=Watford forward Cucho Hernandez to miss Brentford clash with hamstring injury |url=https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/watford-injury-news-brentford-cucho-6958983 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220415134548/https://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/watford-injury-news-brentford-cucho-6958983 |archive-date=2022-04-15 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=HertsLive |language=en}}</ref> He made his return to play in the final match of the season. At the conclusion of the season, Watford would be relegated.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Whitehead |first=Jacob |title=Watford relegated from Premier League after loss to Crystal Palace |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4178982/2022/05/07/watford-relegated-from-premier-league-after-loss-to-crystal-palace/ |access-date=2023-04-25 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-04-25 |title=Cucho 2021-2022 Match Logs |url=https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2021-2022/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425071416/https://fbref.com/en/players/71b47ab9/matchlogs/2021-2022/summary/Cucho-Match-Logs |archive-date=2023-04-25 |access-date=2023-04-25 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref>

===Columbus Crew===

==== 2022 season ====
On 21 June 2022, Hernández agreed to join [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Columbus Crew]] for a club-record fee of [[United States dollar|USD]] $10 million, joining as a [[Designated Player Rule|Young Designated Player]] when the secondary transfer window would open on 7 July 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last=ColumbusCrew.com |title=Columbus Crew acquires 23-year-old forward Juan Camilo "Cucho" Hernandez in record transaction {{!}} Columbus Crew |url=https://www.columbuscrew.com/news/columbus-crew-acquires-23-year-old-forward-juan-camilo-cucho-hernandez-in-record |access-date=2022-10-09 |website=ColumbusCrew.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Cucho Hernandez transfer: Columbus Crew sign Watford's Colombian striker, paying club-record $10 million fee |url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/cucho-hernandez-transfer-columbus-crew-sign-watfords-colombian-striker-paying-club-record-10-million-fee/ |access-date=2022-10-09 |website=CBSSports.com |date=21 June 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=Cucho Hernandez dazzles with game-winner in Columbus Crew debut {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/cucho-hernandez-dazzles-with-game-winner-in-columbus-crew-debut |access-date=2022-10-09 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> Hernández made his debut on 9 July 2022, coming off the bench to score the game winning goal against [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Chicago Fire FC vs Columbus Crew, MLS on Sun, Jul 10, 2022, 24:10 UTC |url=https://www.fotmob.com/match/3787525/matchfacts/chicago-fire-fc-vs-columbus-crew |access-date=2022-10-09 |website=FotMob |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> He would score a brace in the following match in a 2–2 draw vs [[D.C. United]], once again coming off the bench, before getting his first start in MLS versus [[Hell Is Real derby|Hell is Real]] rivals [[FC Cincinnati]], scoring in the 16th minute of an eventual 2–0 victory, becoming the first player in MLS history to score their first four goals in under 90 minutes.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=Josef 2.0? Cucho Hernandez wants "to make my own history" with Columbus Crew {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/josef-2-0-cucho-hernandez-wants-to-make-my-own-history-with-columbus-crew |access-date=2022-07-19 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> On 29 September 2022, it was announced that Hernández had been suspended one match for the use of offensive language in Columbus' match against the [[Portland Timbers]] on 18 September.<ref>{{Cite web |last=mlssoccer |title=Columbus Crew forward Cucho Hernández suspended one game {{!}} MLSSoccer.com |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/columbus-crew-forward-cucho-hernandez-suspended-one-game |access-date=2022-10-09 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> Hernández would end his first season in Major League Soccer with nine goals in 16 total appearances for his new club.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last= |title=Cucho Hernández {{!}} Columbus Crew |url=https://www.columbuscrew.com/players/juan-camilo-hernandez-suarez/stats/ |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=ColumbusCrew.com |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2023 season ====
At the beginning of the [[2023 Columbus Crew season|2023 season]], Hernández started in his side's first three games. After missing the following six games with a knee injury, Hernández would make his return to the team in a [[U.S. Open Cup]] match against [[Indy Eleven]], playing in the first half.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gay |first=Colin |date=April 26, 2023 |title=Cucho Hernandez returns, Columbus Crew offense struggles in 1-0 win vs. Indy Eleven |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/mls/columbus-crew/2023/04/26/columbus-crew-earns-1-0-win-vs-indy-eleven-in-us-open-cup/70156544007/ |access-date=2024-07-25 |website=The Columbus Dispatch |language=en-US}}</ref> He scored his first goal in the 2023 season the following league match against [[Inter Miami CF|Inter Miami]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Miami 2-1 Columbus (Apr 29, 2023) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/659703/inter-miami-cf-columbus-crew |access-date=2024-07-25 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> On 2 September 2023, Hernández scored a hat-trick in a 4–2 victory over [[CF Montréal]], his first since his time at Deportivo Pereira.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Jardy |first=Adam |date=2023-09-02 |title=Cucho Hernandez hat trick leads Columbus Crew to road win against CF Montreal |work=[[The Columbus Dispatch]] |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/mls/columbus-crew/2023/09/02/columbus-crew-wins-at-montreal-thanks-to-cucho-hernandez-hat-trick/70753582007/ |access-date=2023-09-03}}</ref> Hernández scored his second hat-trick for Columbus in a 3–0 victory over the [[Chicago Fire FC|Chicago Fire]] just two matches later.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gay |first=Colin |date=2023-09-20 |title=Cucho Hernandez hat trick clinches Crew postseason berth, beats Chicago Fire FC |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/mls/columbus-crew/2023/09/20/cucho-hernandez-hat-trick-secures-crew-win-vs-chicago-fire-mls-postseason-berth/70914842007/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230922011141/https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/mls/columbus-crew/2023/09/20/cucho-hernandez-hat-trick-secures-crew-win-vs-chicago-fire-mls-postseason-berth/70914842007/ |archive-date=2023-09-22 |access-date=2023-09-22 |website=The Columbus Dispatch |language=en-US}}</ref> His eight goals and one assist across five matches earned him MLS Player of the Month for September.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=Oct 4, 2023 |title=Columbus Crew forward Cucho Hernández named MLS Player of the Month |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/columbus-crew-forward-cucho-hernandez-named-mls-player-of-the-month |access-date=2025-07-31 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> On 9 December, he scored the first goal of the match as Columbus beat [[LAFC]] 2–1 in [[MLS Cup 2023|MLS Cup]], with this title also being the Colombian's first in his career.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2023-12-10 |title=Columbus Crew tops LAFC to win MLS Cup with the exquisite soccer they trademarked all season |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mls-cup-columbus-crew-lafc-championship-202120191.html |access-date=2023-12-14 |website=Yahoo Sports |language=en-US}}</ref> He was later selected as the MLS Cup MVP and included in the Best XI.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=Nov 28, 2023 |title=2023 MLS Best XI presented by Continental Tire |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/2023-mls-best-xi-presented-by-continental-tire |access-date=2025-07-31 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref>

==== 2024 season ====
Hernández started out the new season with four goals across the club's first six matches, including a goal in the [[2024 CONCACAF Champions Cup|Champions Cup]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Liljenwall |first=Ari |date=March 12, 2024 |title=Columbus stave off Houston, advance to Champions Cup quarters |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/columbus-stave-off-houston-advance-to-champions-cup-quarters |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> On 23 March, Hernández was substituted out of the game in the 88th minute during a 0–2 defeat to [[Charlotte FC]], which led to a heated exchange with the assistant coaches.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Arace |first=Michael |date=April 9, 2024 |title=Arace: If you are a Crew fan, you wonder where is Juan Camilo Hernandez Suarez |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/columns/2024/04/09/the-curious-case-of-wilfried-nancy-cucho-hernandez-and-columbus-crew/73240791007/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=September 3, 2024 |website=The Columbus Dispatch}}</ref> Following this altercation, Hernández was suspended for two games, with head coach [[Wilfried Nancy]] citing a violation of "team policy" as the reason for the suspension.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Butler |first=Dylan |date=April 2, 2024 |title=Columbus Crew, Tigres UANL battle to draw in Champions Cup quarters |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/concacaf-champions-cup-columbus-crew-tigres-uanl-battle-to-draw |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> During his first game back from suspension, Hernández received a direct red card for violent conduct, and missed the following match against [[Real Salt Lake]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mac Kay |first=Brianna |title=Columbus Crew avoid home loss with late Aidan Morris goal, finishing 1-1 vs D.C. United |url=https://www.dispatch.com/story/sports/mls/columbus-crew/2024/04/06/columbus-crew-draw-vs-d-c-united-cucho-hernandez-receives-red-card/73227878007/ |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=The Columbus Dispatch |language=en-US}}</ref> He scored in his first game back from red-card suspension against Portland on 20 April.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Columbus 2-2 Portland (Apr 20, 2024) Final Score |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/692721/portland-timbers-columbus-crew |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref> After missing three games due to a back injury, Hernández made his return versus [[C.F. Pachuca|Pachuca]] in the [[2024 CONCACAF Champions Cup final|Champions Cup final]] loss, and subsequently scored nine goals in nine games, including a hat-trick on 22 June versus [[Sporting Kansas City]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Steiner |first=Ben |date=June 23, 2024 |title=Cucho Hernández eyes Golden Boot race with latest hat trick for Crew |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/cucho-hernandez-eyes-golden-boot-race-with-latest-hat-trick-for-crew |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref> The Crew won the [[2024 Leagues Cup]] with a 3–1 victory in the [[2024 Leagues Cup final|final]]. Hernández contributed by scoring two goals and assisting on the third, earning him the Man of the Match title and the Leagues Cup Best Player award for the tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=August 25, 2024 |title=Cucho Hernández & Columbus Crew are Leagues Cup 2024 champions! |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/cucho-hernandez-columbus-crew-are-leagues-cup-2024-champions |access-date=2024-09-02 |website=mlssoccer |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2" />

=== Real Betis ===
On 3 February 2025, Hernández joined [[La Liga]] club [[Real Betis]] on a permanent basis for an undisclosed fee with Columbus entitled to a percentage of any future transfer fees for the player.<ref>{{Cite web |date=3 February 2025 |title=Columbus Crew transfer Juan "Cucho" Hernández to La Liga side Real Betis |url=https://www.columbuscrew.com/news/columbus-crew-transfer-juan-cucho-hernandez-to-la-liga-side-real-betis |access-date=3 February 2025 |website=[[Columbus Crew]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=3 February 2025 |title=El Real Betis y el Columbus Crew SC llegan a un acuerdo para el traspaso del Cucho Hernández |url=https://www.realbetisbalompie.es/noticias/actualidad/el-real-betis-y-el-columbus-crew-sc-llegan-a-un-acuerdo-para-el-traspaso-del-cucho-hernandez-31015 |access-date=3 February 2025 |website=[[Real Betis]] |language=es}}</ref>

==International career==
Hernández has represented [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] at [[Colombia national under-20 football team|under-20 level]], playing in the [[2017 South American U-20 Championship]], as well as the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], where he scored a hat-trick against [[Tahiti national under-20 football team|Tahiti]].<ref>{{cite web |date=29 May 2019 |title=Colombia cruise past Tahiti to reach Round of 16 |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/match/400010624/#match-summary |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190517053716/https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/match/400010624/#match-summary |archive-date=17 May 2019 |access-date=18 July 2020 |publisher=FIFA.com}}</ref> Hernández received his first call up to the senior side on 29 September 2018, and made his full international debut on 17 October, coming on in the 72nd minute, replacing [[Carlos Bacca]] and scoring a brace in a 3–1 friendly win over [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] at [[Red Bull Arena (New Jersey)|Red Bull Arena]] in [[Harrison, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://colombiareports.com/debutant-cucho-hernandez-fires-brace-as-colombia-stroll-past-costa-rica/|title=Debutant 'Cucho' Hernandez fires brace as Colombia strolls past Costa Rica|publisher=[[Colombia Reports]]|date=16 October 2018|access-date=18 July 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Zúñiga |first=Alejandro |date=2018-10-17 |title=La Sele continues to struggle, falls to Colombia, 3-1 |url=https://ticotimes.net/2018/10/17/la-sele-continues-to-struggle-falls-to-colombia-3-1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018042502/http://www.ticotimes.net/2018/10/17/la-sele-continues-to-struggle-falls-to-colombia-3-1 |archive-date=2018-10-18 |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=The Tico Times |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Colombia vs. Costa Rica Match Report – Tuesday October 16, 2018 |url=https://fbref.com/en/matches/84a7a938/Colombia-Costa-Rica-October-16-2018-Friendlies-M |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512033144/https://fbref.com/en/matches/84a7a938/Colombia-Costa-Rica-October-16-2018-Friendlies-M |archive-date=2023-05-12 |access-date=2023-05-12 |website=FBref.com |language=en}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Hernández acquired his nickname "''Cucho"'' at a young age, when his father shaved his head, leading him to bear a resemblance to [[Esteban Cambiasso|Esteban ''"Cuchu"'' Cambiasso]], a prominent Argentine soccer player at the time.<ref>{{cite web |date=17 October 2018 |title=Les contamos por qué le dicen 'Cucho' a Juan Camilo Hernández |trans-title=We will tell you why they call Juan Camilo Hernández 'Cucho' |url=https://www.futbolred.com/seleccion-colombia/por-que-le-dicen-cucho-al-goleador-juan-camilo-hernandez-89142 |access-date=18 July 2020 |publisher=Futbol Red |language=es}}</ref>

He is a fan of [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Quiceno |first=Andrea Mesa |date=2015-04-10 |title=Desde 'chico', Juan Camilo pintaba para ser figura |url=https://deporterisaraldense.com/deportivo-pereira/desde-chico-juan-camilo-pintaba-para-ser-figura/ |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702064233/https://deporterisaraldense.com/deportivo-pereira/desde-chico-juan-camilo-pintaba-para-ser-figura/ |archive-date=2023-07-02 |access-date=2023-07-02 |website=Deporte Risaraldense |language=es}}</ref>

